{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492891"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:49:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:49:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1180"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1180"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.69,0.04,0.19,0.06,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1180"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54254"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1180"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2019-11-21T08:16:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-27T20:47:41+10:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2023-12-12T20:31:04+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-25 12:39:42"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1180"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39754"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"660"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2057"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15265"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39754"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54254"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents with a three day history of episodes of the room spinning. He gives a clear history that the episodes of vertigo commence shortly after looking to the left and each lasts less than 60 seconds. This is associated with some nausea. There is no tinnitus or hearing loss. He is asymptomatic between the episodes. He had coronavirus-19 infection three months ago from which he is now fully recovered. He has a history of hypertension and hypercholesterolemia, on enalapril and ezetimibe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his vital signs are normal. There is non-sustained horizontal\u00a0nystagmus on looking to the left. Otological and neurological examinations are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo","Meniere\u0027s disease","Vestibular neuronitis","Acute labyrinthitis","Cerebellar infarct"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVertigo is a common presentation to general practice. Careful assessment of vertigo is crucial\u00a0as causes of vertigo can range from benign causes including \u003Cstrong\u003Ebenign paroxysmal positional vertigo\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Evestibular neuronitis \u003C/strong\u003Ewhich are usually self-limiting to serious causes including \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebrovascular accidents or other neurological diseases\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first step in assessment vertigo is to determine whether it is from a peripheral cause (ie otological system) or central cause (ie neurological system). Central causes of vertigo tend to be more sustained and associated with other focal neurology. Peripheral causes is usually more associated with otological symptoms e.g. hearing loss. Ear, neurological and eye examination is important in vertigo as otological abnormalities may point to peripheral cause, neurological abnormalities may point to central cause and the type of nystagmus can also differentiate between peripheral and central cause. For more information on assessment of vertigo please see reference below.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECovid-19 infections may be associated with vestibular disturbances but requires ongoing studies and the reasoning and the link is still unclear at this stage. \u003Cstrong\u003EVestibular neuritis\u003C/strong\u003E does present similarly to BPPV with seconds to minutes of dizziness and aggravating symptoms with change of head movement, however it is more likely to be present when still as well as on movement. Vestibular neuronitis is caused by inflammation to the vestibular nerve. Classic presentation is sudden onset of severe vertigo associated with loss of balance without hearing loss or tinnitus.  Vestibular neuritis is associated with recent upper respiratory tract infections however the patient\u0027s infection was a longer duration previously (three months) instead. There often is more balance disturbance associated with vestibular neuritis, and catch-up sacaade seen on rapid movement to the affected side. These features make this presentation more likely to have peripheral vertigo secondary to BPPV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient likely has peripheral vertigo because it is non-sustained and not associated with focal neurology.\u003Cstrong\u003E Benign Paroxysmal Positional vertigo \u003C/strong\u003Eis\u00a0caused by an accumulation of calcium crystals in the posterior semicircular canal which affects the movement of endolymph in the canals causing vertigo.  Patients typically present with episodes of seconds of vertigo aggravated with head movement and resolves spontaneously.  The patient presents well in between.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute labyrinthitis\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by inflammation of the labyrinth (often due to viral infection) and classically\u00a0presents with both vertigo and hearing loss. \u003Cstrong\u003EMeniere\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E classically presents with episodes of vertigo lasting longer than 20 minutes, tinnitus, sensorineural hearing loss and aural fullness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["BPPV is characterized by brief episodes of vertigo associated with head movement, Vestibular Neuronitis presents with sudden onset severe vertigo and no hearing loss.","Meniere\u0027s disease is characterized by longer episodes of vertigo, tinnitus, sensorineural hearing loss, and aural fullness.","A recent viral infection is associated with labyrinthitis and neuronitis."],"references":["Dommaraju S, Perera E. An approach to vertigo in general practice. Australian family physician. 2016 Apr;45(4):190-4."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39754"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1180"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39754"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-02T11:58:35+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-27T20:48:13+10:30","number":8,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2024-10-27T20:47:41+10:30","plagiarismScore":11.1,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-1180-8.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250928%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250928T211903Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=7fc8d3f46ece2e0f25b4ae8b77b76bf14b2a88570d0c75ad50007d356b92f57b"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1180"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54254"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"13477"}},"generation":{"data":nu